Finding the Regression



Using the dataset prepared here , the following outlines the steps I made to find a good regression for the data.



I first imported and made training and test datasets.





  • SWE + Month + SWE:Month + avg_temp, .934 correlation





  • Same model, SWE has a sqrt transformation, .925 correlation





This model produces negative snow depth values, and has an unfavorable data shape.

The squared residuals from the original model also show a megaphone shape. I did a Box Cox for a possible Y transformation.







This suggests a .6 transformation, but I decided to do a .5, just for simplicity.



  • SQRT(Depth) ~ SQRT(SWE) + Month + SQRT(SWE) + avg_temp, .94 correlation.





Best correlation, data is mostly linear. Interesting patterns in residuals. I decided to use this model. Megaphone shape greatly reduced.





  • Validation Set: .9405 correlation





Model has similar linearity, and correlation, which helps us have confidence in that model has similar results for supposedly similar data, and that model wasn’t over-fitting first data.



  • Full Dataset: .94 correlation







Residuals are almost normally distributed, just a little steep. But maybe the more important thing to take away this the model errors mostly within 5 of actual values.

This model was used to predict the missing snow depth values.
